S1.T1.caption: TABLE I:  Zero-shot, out-of-domain evaluation on three open type NER speech benchmarks. The Params column indicate the extra parameters of baseline methods w.r.t WhisperNER. We bold the best results and underline the second-best results.
references: We first evaluate WhisperNER on the three open-type NER benchmarks, namely VoxPopuli-NER, LibriSpeech-NER and Fleurs-NER. Each test example is annotated with positive NER tags based on the annotation scheme of [9]. To construct negative samples, we randomly sample negative NER labels from the entire dataset. We ensure that the number of negative NER labels matches the number of positive labels, resulting in a balanced dataset. The results are presented in Table I. both WhisperNER variants outperform all baseline methods in terms of NER F1 score, with only a slight decrease in WER, while being more parameter-efficient.

S3.T2.caption: TABLE II:  Zero-Shot Performance on the MIT NER Benchmarks.
references: Next, we evaluate the zero-shot NER performance of our WhisperNER and WhisperNER-BIO models on the closed set entity sets of the MIT NER benchmarks [18]. The results are summarized in Table II. In this setup, WhisperNER does not perform as well as the baselines in terms of NER F1, showing a higher tendency to incorrectly tag non-entity spans. Recognizing these limitations, we identify areas for refinement and believe that a more in-depth analysis, and further enhancements, hold potential for significant improvements. We leave these pursuits for future research, focusing on optimizing WhisperNER to better handle closed set zero-shot scenarios.

S3.T3.caption: TABLE III:  Supervised FT Performance on the MIT NER Benchmarks.
references: Finally, we evaluate the supervised fine-tuning performance of our WhisperNER model on common NER benchmarks, with results summarized in Table III. For this experiment, the methods were fine-tuned on labeled datasets to assess their ability to recognize and tag entities in a supervised setting. For the baseline methods, we independently finetune both the Whipser model, and the NER baseline. Our method outperforms all baselines, achieving the best performance in both WER and NER F1 scores. These improvements demonstrate the effectiveness of our approach in jointly handling transcription and entity recognition tasks, further validating WhisperNER’s capability to generalize to structured NER datasets in a supervised setting.

S3.T4.caption: TABLE IV:  Effect of negative sampling approach: We evaluate WhisperNER models trained using the NuNER dataset for 25K steps, on the zero-shot task over the MIT NER Benchmarks.
references: Table IV shows that using full entity sets from negative examples, "random sample", consistently outperforms random negative sampling of NER types, likely due to the contextual consistency of the selected examples. We also tested a "hard negative" approach, where negative examples are chosen based on semantic similarity to positive examples. While this method performed comparably, it introduced additional overhead in querying the dataset, hence we opt for random sampling from the training set for efficiency.
